
[1]piracy

   PI'RACY, n. [L. piratica, from Gr. to attempt, to dare, to enterprise,
   whence L. periculum, experior; Eng. to fare.]

   1. The act, practice or crime of robbing on the high seas; the taking
   of property from others by open violence and without authority, on the
   sea; a crime that answers to robbery on land.

   Other acts than robbery on the high seas, are declared by statute to be
   piracy. See Act of Congress, April 30, 1790.

   2. The robbing of another by taking his writings.
